paper_1.title: The Network Dynamics Hypothesis: How Channel Networks Structure Riverine Habitats
paper_1.mechanism: Abrupt changes in flow and sediment flux at network confluences create discontinuities that generate habitat diversity. The hierarchical branching structure of the network determines how these discontinuities are distributed in space, with network geometry regulating the spatial pattern of physical diversity.

paper_1.title: Averaged pulse dynamics in a cascaded transmission system with passive dispersion compensation
paper_1.mechanism: In systems with periodic variation between two regimes (like dispersion and compensation), pulse dynamics can be described by averaged equations when the variation period is much shorter than the evolution scale. The fast variations average out, leaving an effective dynamics governed by residual parameters.

paper_2.title: Tipping points: Early warning and wishful thinking
paper_2.mechanism: Rapid system transitions can arise from two mechanisms: bifurcations where system stability changes (predictable from critical slowing) or noise-induced jumps between stable states (unpredictable). Analysis of transition precursors can distinguish between these mechanisms and assess predictability limits.
